Thanks for the detailed explanation! This is a great rendering challenge.

The issue with Approach 2 (1×512 bitmap + rotation) is that at radius 512, your 2048 spokes have an angular step of ~0.176°, which corresponds to arc gaps of ~1.6 pixels — so pixels at the outer edge get missed.

**Recommended approaches:**

**Option A — DrawLine per spoke (~2048 draw calls)**
Instead of DrawCircle for every pixel, draw one line per spoke. Configure an `SKPaint` with the dominant color of the spoke:
```csharp
using var paint = new SKPaint { StrokeWidth = 1, IsAntialias = true };
for (int i = 0; i < 2048; i++)
{
    double rad = i * Math.PI * 2 / 2048;
    float endX = (float)(cx + Math.Cos(rad) * 512);
    float endY = (float)(cy + Math.Sin(rad) * 512);
    paint.Color = spokeColor[i]; // pick representative color for spoke
    canvas.DrawLine(cx, cy, endX, endY, paint);
}
```
This is ~500× fewer draw calls than your Approach 1.

**Option B — Pre-render a full polar bitmap (no moiré, single DrawBitmap per frame)**
For full per-pixel color fidelity, iterate the destination bitmap pixels in cartesian space and reverse-map to polar:
```csharp
using var bmp = new SKBitmap(1024, 1024, SKColorType.Bgra8888, SKAlphaType.Premul);
unsafe
{
    var ptr = (uint*)bmp.GetPixels().ToPointer();
    for (int py = 0; py < 1024; py++)
    for (int px = 0; px < 1024; px++)
    {
        float dx = px - 512, dy = py - 512;
        float r = MathF.Sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy);
        if (r < 1 || r > 512) continue;
        float angle = MathF.Atan2(dy, dx); // -PI..PI
        if (angle < 0) angle += MathF.PI * 2;
        int spokeIdx = (int)(angle / (MathF.PI * 2) * 2048) % 2048;
        int dist = (int)r;
        ptr[py * 1024 + px] = (uint)spoke[spokeIdx][dist].ToArgb();
    }
}
canvas.DrawBitmap(bmp, 0, 0);
```
This gives pixel-perfect rendering with zero gaps.
